of mammary ducts","Autoimmune destruction of mammary ducts","Hormonal stimulation causing ductal hyperplasia","Bacterial infection of mammary ducts","Neoplastic transformation of ductal epithelium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of mammary duct ectasia, including periareolar mass, nipple discharge, and nipple retraction. The condition primarily affects women in their 40s and 50s, with smoking being a significant risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgressive dilation and inflammation of mammary ducts\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct pathogenesis. The process begins with dilation of the major ducts, followed by stasis of secretions and subsequent inflammatory response. This leads to periductal fibrosis and potential nipple retraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of mammary ducts\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised mechanism for duct ectasia. While inflammatory changes occur, they are secondary to the ductal dilation rather than autoimmune-mediated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial infection of mammary ducts\u003C/strong\u003E may occur as a complication of duct ectasia but is not the primary pathogenic mechanism. The initial process is mechanical rather than infectious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormonal stimulation causing ductal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E better describes conditions like fibrocystic changes or gynecomastia. Duct ectasia is not primarily hormone-dependent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoplastic transformation of ductal epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E describes the pathogenesis of ductal carcinoma, not duct ectasia. While duct ectasia can mimic cancer clinically, it is a benign inflammatory condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mammary duct ectasia is a benign condition characterised by dilated ducts and periductal inflammation.","The condition typically affects women in their 40s and 50s and can mimic breast cancer clinically.","Smoking is a significant risk factor for mammary duct ectasia.","It presents with nipple discharge of varying consistency and colour, usually unilateral and from a single duct."],"references":["Hamwi MW, Winters R. Mammary Duct Ectasia. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK557665/","Mohammed AA. Mammary duct ectasia in adult females; risk factors for the disease, a case control study. Ann Med Surg (Lond). 2021 Jan 18;62:140-144. doi: 10.1016/j.amsu.2021.01.023. PMID: 33520211; PMCID: PMC7820305.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16220"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T18:28:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T18:28:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8911"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attri